{"title_page": "Chu Lai Base Area", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox military installation\n| name = Chu Lai Base Area\n| ensign = [[File:Emblem of the United States Marine Corps.svg|60px]]&nbsp;[[File:Military service mark of the United States Army.svg|60px]]\n| ensign_size =\n| native_name = \n| location = [[Chu Lai]], [[Qu\u1ea3ng Nam Province]]\n| country = Vietnam\n| image = Helicopters at Chu Lai Airfield, 1966 (16706932455).jpg\n| alt = Helicopters at Chu Lai, 1966\n| coordinates = {{Coord|15.455|N|108.69|E|display=inline|name=Chu Lai Base Area}}\n| built = {{Start date|1965}}\n| used = 1965-{{End date|1972}}\n| builder = \n| materials =\n| condition = \n| battles = [[File:Vietnam Service Medal ribbon.svg|60px]]<br>[[Vietnam War]]<br>[[Operation Starlite]]\n| occupants = [[3rd Marine Division]]<br>[[1st Marine Division]]<br>[[Task Force Oregon]]<br>[[23rd Infantry Division (United States)|23rd Americal Division]]\n<!-- begin airfield information  -->\n| IATA = \n| ICAO = \n| FAA = \n| TC = \n| LID = \n| GPS = \n| WMO = \n| elevation = {{Convert|1759|ft|0}}\n| r1-number = \n| r1-length = \n| r1-surface = \n| h1-number = 03/21\n| h1-length = {{Convert|660|ft|0}}\n| h1-surface = Asphalt\n}}\n'''Chu Lai Base Area''' (also known as '''Chu Lai Combat Base''' or simply '''Chu Lai''' or '''K\u1ef3 H\u00e0''') is a former U.S. Marine Corps, U.S. Army and [[Army of the Republic of Vietnam]] (ARVN) base in [[Chu Lai]] in central [[Vietnam]].\n\n'''K\u1ef3 H\u00e0 Air Facility''' was part of the installation and was located in the northern half, '''[[Chu Lai Air Base]]''' was part of the installation and was located to the south-east. \n \n==History==\n\n===1965===\nThe base was located on the K\u1ef3 H\u00e0 peninsula north of [[National Route 1A (Vietnam)|Highway 1]] approximately {{Convert|60|km}} southeast of Da Nang.<ref name=Kelley>{{cite book|last=Kelley|first=Michael|title=Where we were in Vietnam|publisher=Hellgate Press|year=2002|isbn=978-1555716257|pages=5\u2013284}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 May units from the ARVN [[2nd Division (South Vietnam)|2nd Division]] and [[3rd Battalion, 9th Marines]] secured the Chu Lai area. On 7 May, the [[3rd Marine Expeditionary Brigade (United States)|3rd Marine Expeditionary Brigade]] (3rd MEB), composed of the [[4th Marine Regiment]], [[3rd Reconnaissance Battalion]], elements of [[Marine Aircraft Group 12]] (MAG-12) and Naval Mobile Construction Battalion 10 landed at Chu Lai to establish a [[Chu Lai Air Base|jet-capable airfield]] and base area.<ref name=Shulimson65>{{cite book|last=Shulimson|first=Jack|title=U.S. Marines in Vietnam: The Landing and the Buildup|publisher=History and Museums Division, Headquarters, U.S. Marine Corps|year=1978|isbn=978-1494287559}}{{PD-notice}}</ref>{{rp|29-35}}\n\nThe Marines provided security for the Seabees as they constructed the airbase. By mid-June the [[3rd Battalion, 12th Marines]] had arrived at Chu Lai to provide artillery support for the 4th Marines and the Marines were authorised to conduct search and destroy operations within a 104 square mile tactical area of operations.<ref name=Shulimson65/>{{rp|46\u20138}}\n\nIn August [[3rd Battalion, 11th Marines]] and the 3rd 155mm Gun Battery arrived at Chu Lai.<ref name=Shulimson65/>{{rp|164}} On 14 August the [[7th Marine Regiment]] arrived at Chu Lai.<ref name=Shulimson65/>{{rp|65}} On 18 August the Marines launched [[Operation Starlite]] to secure the area around Chu Lai, the operation lasted until 24 August and resulted in 45 Marines and 614 [[Viet Cong]] killed.<ref name=Shulimson65/>{{rp|80}}\n\nOn 2 September [[Marine Aircraft Group 36]] (MAG-36) was established at K\u1ef3 H\u00e0,<ref name=Shulimson65/>{{rp|148}} comprising:\n*[[VMM-362|HMM-362]]\n*[[VMM-363|HMM-363]] (from December)\n*[[VMM-364|HMM-364]]\n*[[Marine Aviation Logistics Squadron 36|H&MS-36]] \n*[[VMO-6]]<ref name=Popasmoke>{{cite web|url=http://www.popasmoke.com/vw-order-of-battle|title=Order of Battle|publisher=USMC Combat Helicopter Association|accessdate=5 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nAlso in September the [[3rd Low Altitude Air Defense Battalion#Ground Based Air Defense in Vietnam|2nd Light Anti-Aircraft Missile Battalion]] equipped with [[MIM-23 Hawk|HAWK missiles]] was deployed to Chu Lai to defend the air base and base area.<ref name=Shulimson65/>{{rp|118}}\n\nIn November [[3rd Battalion, 3rd Marines]] was moved from Chu Lai to Danang.<ref name=Shulimson65/>{{rp|96}} By the end of 5 December Marine Battalions from the 4th and 7th Marine Regiments were based at Chu Lai.<ref name=Shulimson65/>{{rp|118}}\n\nWhen initially established the air base and base area were supplied by [[Landing Ship, Tank|LSTs]] coming from Danang and landing at an LST ramp built on the sheltered side of the K\u1ef3 H\u00e0 Peninsula. A Force Logistic Support Unit was established on the K\u1ef3 H\u00e0 Peninsula to control the logistics flow.<ref name=Shulimson65/>{{rp|185}}\n\n===1966===\n[[File:Chu Lai Fleet Logistics Support Group Bravo.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Force Logistics Support Group Bravo]]\nOn 17 January the [[1st Marine Regiment]] established its headquarters at Chu Lai and later took operational control of the two battalions of the 4th Marines.<ref name=Shulimson66>{{cite book|last=Shulimson|first=Jack|title=U.S. Marines in Vietnam: An Expanding War 1966|publisher=History and Museums Division, Headquarters, U.S. Marine Corps|year=1982|isbn=978-1494285159}}{{PD-notice}}</ref>{{rp|19}} In late January the Marine infantry and helicopters at Chu Lai participated in [[Operation Double Eagle]]<ref name=Shulimson66/>{{rp|19\u201336}} On 27 February while several Battalions were absent on Operation Double Eagle the Vietcong attacked a 1/4 Marines outpost killing 5 Marines.<ref name=Shulimson66/>{{rp|36}}\n\nFrom 4\u20137 March the Chu Lai-based Marines and ARVN 2nd Division launched [[Operation Utah]] resulting in 98 Marines, 30 ARVN and almost 600 [[People's Army of Vietnam]] (PAVN) soldiers killed and 5 captured.<ref name=Shulimson66/>{{rp|109\u2013119}} From 20\u201327 March the 3/7 Marines and ARVN [[Republic of Vietnam Airborne Division|5th Airborne Battalion]] launched [[Operation Texas (1966)|Operation Texas]] resulting in 99 Marines and 283 PAVN/Vietcong killed.<ref name=Shulimson66/>{{rp|120\u20136}} On 28 March the 1/7 Marines launched [[Operation Indiana]] to assist the 3rd Battalion, 5th ARVN Regiment resulting in 11 Marines and 169 Vietcong killed.<ref name=Shulimson66/>{{rp|127\u20138}}\n\nOn 28 March 4 Marines moved their headquarters from Chu Lai to [[Phu Bai Combat Base]]<ref name=Shulimson66/>{{rp|69}} The 3/12 Marines also moved to Phu Bai in March and artillery support was taken over by the 11th Marines.<ref name=Shulimson66/>{{rp|277}}\n\nOn 29 March the [[1st Marine Division]] established its headquarters at Chu Lai. The 1st Division commander MGEN Lewis Fields created the Chu Lai Defense Command tasked with protecting the air base and the K\u1ef3 H\u00e0 Peninsula.<ref name=Shulimson66/>{{rp|128\u20139}}\n\nAlso in March the Force Logistics Support Unit became Force Logistics Support Group Bravo and [[Naval Mobile Construction Battalion 4]] began building permanent facilities at K\u1ef3 H\u00e0.<ref name=Shulimson66/>{{rp|288\u20139}}\n\nIn mid-April the [[2nd Battalion, 5th Marines]] replaced the 2/4 Marines which moved north to Danang. On 22 May [[1st Battalion, 5th Marines]] replaced the 3/1 Marines which also moved to Danang. On 27 May the [[5th Marine Regiment]] moved its headquarters to Chu Lai. By 1 June Marine Division had over 17,000 men in the expanded 340 square mile tactical area of operations around Chu Lai.<ref name=Shulimson66/>{{rp|130\u20131}}\n\nFrom 17\u201322 June 1 Marine Division launched [[Operation Kansas]] in the [[Que Son Valley]] resulting in 9 Marines and 85 PAVN killed.<ref name=Shulimson66/>{{rp|131\u20136}} From 6\u201314 July the Marines [[1st Reconnaissance Battalion]] launched [[Operation Washington]] in the [[Do Xa]] region west of Chu Lai, resulting in 15 Vietcong killed and 8 captured.<ref name=Shulimson66/>{{rp|212\u20133}} From 6\u201322 August the Marines and ARVN launched [[Operation Colorado|Operation Colorado/Lien Ket 52]] to engage the PAVN [[2nd Division (Vietnam)|2nd Division]] in the Que Son Valley.<ref name=Shulimson66/>{{rp|214\u201320}}\n\nOn 18 August the [[Republic of Korea]] [[2nd Marine Division (South Korea)|2nd Marine Brigade]] was deployed to Chu Lai and assigned an area of operations southeast of Chu lai, including the [[Batangan Peninsula]].<ref name=Shulimson66/>{{rp|223}}\n\nOn 10 October 1 Marine Division headquarters was moved from Chu Lai to Danang, replacing the 3rd Marine Division rear headquarters which moved from Danang to [[\u0110\u00f4ng H\u00e0 Combat Base|\u0110\u00f4ng H\u00e0]].<ref name=Shulimson66/>{{rp|223}}\n\nIn October [[94th Field Artillery Regiment|Battery A, 2nd Battalion, 18th Artillery]] was deployed to Chu Lai to support the Marine artillery. On 30 November the [[1st Field Artillery Group]] was deployed to Chu Lai to assume control of all artillery from the 11th Marines which had moved north to Danang.<ref name=Shulimson66/>{{rp|279\u201380}}\n\nUnits attached to MAG-36 at K\u1ef3 H\u00e0 during this period included:\n*[[VMM-165|HMM-165]] (from September)\n*[[VMM-261|HMM-261]] (until April)\n*[[VMM-262|HMM-262]] (from December)\n*[[HMH-361|HMM-361]] (June, August)\n*HMM-362 (April\u2013August)\n*HMM-363 (until July)\n*HMM-364 (until March, July\u2013October)\n*[[Marine Aviation Logistics Squadron 16|H&MS-16]] sub-unit one (January 1966)\n*VMO-6<ref name=Popasmoke/>\n\n===1967===\nFrom 21 April to 16 May the Marines launched [[Operation Union]] near the Que Son Valley resulting in 110 Marines and 865 PAVN/Vietcong killed.<ref name=Telfer>{{cite book|last=Telfer|first=Gary|title=U.S. Marines in Vietnam: Fighting the North Vietnamese 1967|publisher=History and Museums Division, Headquarters, U.S. Marine Corps|year=1984|isbn=978-1494285449}}{{PD-notice}}</ref>{{rp|63-8}}\n\nIn early April [[Military Assistance Command, Vietnam]] (MACV) gave instructions to commence the [[Task Force Oregon]] plan, which involved the movement of an Army task force to [[\u0110\u1ee9c Ph\u1ed5 Base Camp|\u0110\u1ee9c Ph\u1ed5]] and Chu Lai area to allow the 1st Marine Division to move north to Danang to support the 3rd Marine Division in northern I Corps.<ref name=Telfer/>{{rp|78}}<ref name=Stanton>{{cite book|last=Stanton|first=Shelby|title=Vietnam Order of Battle|publisher=Stackpole Books|year=2003|isbn=9780811700719|page=85}}</ref> Task Force Oregon comprised:\n*[[25th Infantry Division (United States)|3rd Brigade, 25th Infantry Division]]\n*[[101st Airborne Division|1st Brigade, 101st Airborne Division]]\n*[[196th Infantry Brigade (United States)|196th Light Infantry Brigade]]\n*[[11th Armored Cavalry Regiment|2nd Squadron, 11th Armored Cavalry]] (May\u2013August 1967)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|131}}\n\nOn 9 April the 196th Light Infantry Brigade arrived at Chu Lai, the Task Force headquarters was activated on 12 April, by 17 April the 196th had commenced [[Operation Lawrence]] west of the air base and by 26 April the Task Force had assumed control of the Chu Lai tactical area of operations.<ref name=Telfer/>{{rp|79}}\n\nFrom August\u2013September Task Force Oregon launched [[Operation Benton]] to the west of Chu Lai, resulting in 397 PAVN killed.<ref name=Telfer/>{{rp|119}}\n\nIn September 1967 the [[23rd Infantry Division (United States)|23rd Infantry Division]] was reestablished from elements of Task Force Oregon with its headquarters at Chu Lai and would remain here until November 1971,<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|79}} its subordinate units based at Chu Lai were:\n*[[1st Cavalry Regiment (United States)|1st Squadron, 1st Cavalry]] (September 1967 \u2013 November 1968, November 1969 \u2013 August 1970, November 1970 \u2013 April 1971)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|124}}\n*[[11th Infantry Brigade (United States)|11th Infantry Brigade]]<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|85}}\n*196th Light Infantry Brigade (June\u2013October 1967, July 1968 \u2013 March 1971)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|88}}\n*[[198th Infantry Brigade (United States)|198th Infantry Brigade]] (December 1967 \u2013 November 1971)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|88}}\n*[[16th Field Artillery Regiment|3rd Battalion, 16th Artillery]] (June 1967 \u2013 October 1971)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|100}}\n*[[18th Field Artillery Regiment|3rd Battalion, 18th Artillery]] (April 1967 \u2013 October 1971)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|101}}\n*[[55th Air Defense Artillery Regiment|Battery G, 55th Artillery]] (February 1968 \u2013 July 1971)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|105}}\n*[[56th Air Defense Artillery Regiment|6th Battalion, 56th Artillery]] (1968 \u2013 June 1969)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|105}}\n*[[82nd Field Artillery Regiment|1st Battalion, 82nd Artillery]] (July 1968 \u2013 November 1971)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|107}}\n*[[82nd Field Artillery Regiment|3rd Battalion, 82nd Artillery]] (February 1969)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|107}}\n*[[16th Combat Aviation Brigade (United States)|16th Aviation Group]] (March 1969 \u2013 November 1971)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|110}} including:\n**[[14th Aviation Battalion]] (April 1967 \u2013 October 1971)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|114}}\n**[[123rd Aviation Battalion]] (December 1967 \u2013 November 1971)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|115}}\n**[[21st Aviation Company]] (June 1967 \u2013 November 1971)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|121}}\n**[[71st Aviation Company]] (September 1967 \u2013 October 1971)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|121}}\n*[[28th Engineer Battalion]] (December 1967 \u2013 November 1971)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|171}}\n*[[509th Signal Battalion]] (1967\u201368)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|185}}\n*[[523rd Signal Battalion]] (January 1968 \u2013 November 1971)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|185}}\n*[[74th Medical Battalion]] (October 1967 \u2013 November 1969)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|213}}\n*[[27th Surgical Hospital]] (March 1968 \u2013 June 1971)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|215}}\n*[[91st Evacuation Hospital]] (July 1969 \u2013 November 1971)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|216}}\n\nUnits attached to MAG-36 at K\u1ef3 H\u00e0 during this period included:\n*HMM-165 (until November)\n*[[HMM-263]] (from July\u2013November)\n*HMM-262 (until March)\n*HMM-362 (until June)\n*HMM-363 (January)\n*VMO-6 (until September)<ref name=Popasmoke/>\n\nIn October MAG-36 began to relocate from K\u1ef3 H\u00e0 to Phu Bai and by the end of the month most units had completed the move.<ref name=Telfer/>{{rp|211}}\n\nThe [[3rd Brigade Combat Team, 1st Cavalry Division|3rd Brigade, 1st Cavalry Division]] was based at Chu Lai from October 1967 \u2013 January 1968, constituent units included:\n*[[7th Cavalry Regiment|1st Battalion, 7th Cavalry]] (January 1968)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|127}}\n*[[7th Cavalry Regiment|2nd Battalion, 7th Cavalry]]<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|127}}\n*[[12th Cavalry Regiment|2nd Battalion, 12th Cavalry]] (October 1967 \u2013 January 1968)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|132}}\n\nIn late 1967 Force Logistics Group Bravo moved from Chu Lai to \u0110\u00f4ng H\u00e0, leaving only a reinforced supply company to handle logistics for the remaining Marines at Chu Lai.<ref name=Telfer/>{{rp|229}}\n\nIn 1967 a Naval Support Activity base was established at Chu Lai to provide logistics support for allied operations in southern I Corps.<ref name=Telfer/>{{rp|232}}\n\n===1968\u201371===\nOn 31 January 1968 as part of the [[Tet Offensive]] Vietcong rockets hit the FLSG Bravo ammunition dump destroying over 600 tons of bombs and bulk explosives.<ref name=Shulimson>{{cite book|last=Shulimson|first=Jack|title=U.S. Marines in Vietnam: 1968 The Defining Year|publisher=History and Museums Division, Headquarters, U.S. Marine Corps|year=1997|isbn= 0-16-049125-8}}{{PD-notice}}</ref>{{rp|583}}\n\nIn September 1968 the 2nd Light Anti-Aircraft Missile Battalion returned to the U.S.<ref name=Shulimson/>{{rp|414}}\n\nOn 27 November 1971 the 23rd Infantry Division turned over the base to the ARVN.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vietnam.ttu.edu/reports/images.php?img=/images/1683/168300010817.pdf|title=Headquarters MACV Command History 1971 Volume II|publisher=Headquarters United States Military Assistance Command, Vietnam|date=1971|accessdate=9 April 2020|page=J-37}}{{PD-notice}}</ref>\n\n==Current use==\nSatellite imagery shows that he base has been turned over to housing and farmland, while the port facilities remain in use.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Marine Corps}}\n\n[[Category:Military installations of the United States Marine Corps in South Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Installations of the United States Army in South Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Installations of the Army of the Republic of Vietnam]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox military installation\n| name = Chu Lai Base Area\n| ensign = [[File:Emblem of the United States Marine Corps.svg|60px]]&nbsp;[[File:Military service mark of the United States Army.svg|60px]]\n| ensign_size =\n| native_name = \n| location = [[Chu Lai]], [[Qu\u1ea3ng Nam Province]]\n| country = Vietnam\n| image = Helicopters at Chu Lai Airfield, 1966 (16706932455).jpg\n| alt = Helicopters at Chu Lai, 1966\n| coordinates = {{Coord|15.455|N|108.69|E|display=inline|name=Chu Lai Base Area}}\n| built = {{Start date|1965}}\n| used = 1965-{{End date|1972}}\n| builder = \n| materials =\n| condition = \n| battles = [[File:Vietnam Service Medal ribbon.svg|60px]]<br>[[Vietnam War]]<br>[[Operation Starlite]]\n| occupants = [[3rd Marine Division]]<br>[[1st Marine Division]]<br>[[Task Force Oregon]]<br>[[23rd Infantry Division (United States)|23rd Americal Division]]\n<!-- begin airfield information  -->\n| IATA = \n| ICAO = \n| FAA = \n| TC = \n| LID = \n| GPS = \n| WMO = \n| elevation = {{Convert|1759|ft|0}}\n| r1-number = \n| r1-length = \n| r1-surface = \n| h1-number = 03/21\n| h1-length = {{Convert|660|ft|0}}\n| h1-surface = Asphalt\n}}\n'''Chu Lai Base Area''' (also known as '''Chu Lai Combat Base''' or simply '''Chu Lai''' or '''K\u1ef3 H\u00e0''') is a former U.S. Marine Corps, U.S. Army and [[Army of the Republic of Vietnam]] (ARVN) base in [[Chu Lai]] in central [[Vietnam]].\n\n'''K\u1ef3 H\u00e0 Air Facility''' was part of the installation and was located in the northern half, '''[[Chu Lai Air Base]]''' was part of the installation and was located to the south-east. \n \n==History==\n\n===1965===\nThe base was located on the K\u1ef3 H\u00e0 peninsula north of [[National Route 1A (Vietnam)|Highway 1]] approximately {{Convert|60|km}} southeast of Da Nang.<ref name=Kelley>{{cite book|last=Kelley|first=Michael|title=Where we were in Vietnam|publisher=Hellgate Press|year=2002|isbn=978-1555716257|pages=5\u2013284}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 May units from the ARVN [[2nd Division (South Vietnam)|2nd Division]] and [[3rd Battalion, 9th Marines]] secured the Chu Lai area. On 7 May, the [[3rd Marine Expeditionary Brigade (United States)|3rd Marine Expeditionary Brigade]] (3rd MEB), composed of the [[4th Marine Regiment]], [[3rd Reconnaissance Battalion]], elements of [[Marine Aircraft Group 12]] (MAG-12) and Naval Mobile Construction Battalion 10 landed at Chu Lai to establish a [[Chu Lai Air Base|jet-capable airfield]] and base area.<ref name=Shulimson65>{{cite book|last=Shulimson|first=Jack|title=U.S. Marines in Vietnam: The Landing and the Buildup|publisher=History and Museums Division, Headquarters, U.S. Marine Corps|year=1978|isbn=978-1494287559}}{{PD-notice}}</ref>{{rp|29-35}}\n\nThe Marines provided security for the Seabees as they constructed the airbase. By mid-June the [[3rd Battalion, 12th Marines]] had arrived at Chu Lai to provide artillery support for the 4th Marines and the Marines were authorised to conduct search and destroy operations within a 104 square mile tactical area of operations.<ref name=Shulimson65/>{{rp|46\u20138}}\n\nIn August [[3rd Battalion, 11th Marines]] and the 3rd 155mm Gun Battery arrived at Chu Lai.<ref name=Shulimson65/>{{rp|164}} On 14 August the [[7th Marine Regiment]] arrived at Chu Lai.<ref name=Shulimson65/>{{rp|65}} On 18 August the Marines launched [[Operation Starlite]] to secure the area around Chu Lai, the operation lasted until 24 August and resulted in 45 Marines and 614 [[Viet Cong]] killed.<ref name=Shulimson65/>{{rp|80}}\n\nOn 2 September [[Marine Aircraft Group 36]] (MAG-36) was established at K\u1ef3 H\u00e0,<ref name=Shulimson65/>{{rp|148}} comprising:\n*[[VMM-362|HMM-362]]\n*[[VMM-363|HMM-363]] (from December)\n*[[VMM-364|HMM-364]]\n*[[Marine Aviation Logistics Squadron 36|H&MS-36]] \n*[[VMO-6]]<ref name=Popasmoke>{{cite web|url=http://www.popasmoke.com/vw-order-of-battle|title=Order of Battle|publisher=USMC Combat Helicopter Association|accessdate=5 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nAlso in September the [[3rd Low Altitude Air Defense Battalion#Ground Based Air Defense in Vietnam|2nd Light Anti-Aircraft Missile Battalion]] equipped with [[MIM-23 Hawk|HAWK missiles]] was deployed to Chu Lai to defend the air base and base area.<ref name=Shulimson65/>{{rp|118}}\n\nIn November [[3rd Battalion, 3rd Marines]] was moved from Chu Lai to Danang.<ref name=Shulimson65/>{{rp|96}} By the end of 5 December Marine Battalions from the 4th and 7th Marine Regiments were based at Chu Lai.<ref name=Shulimson65/>{{rp|118}}\n\nWhen initially established the air base and base area were supplied by [[Landing Ship, Tank|LSTs]] coming from Danang and landing at an LST ramp built on the sheltered side of the K\u1ef3 H\u00e0 Peninsula. A Force Logistic Support Unit was established on the K\u1ef3 H\u00e0 Peninsula to control the logistics flow.<ref name=Shulimson65/>{{rp|185}}\n\n===1966===\n[[File:Chu Lai Fleet Logistics Support Group Bravo.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Force Logistics Support Group Bravo]]\nOn 17 January the [[1st Marine Regiment]] established its headquarters at Chu Lai and later took operational control of the two battalions of the 4th Marines.<ref name=Shulimson66>{{cite book|last=Shulimson|first=Jack|title=U.S. Marines in Vietnam: An Expanding War 1966|publisher=History and Museums Division, Headquarters, U.S. Marine Corps|year=1982|isbn=978-1494285159}}{{PD-notice}}</ref>{{rp|19}} In late January the Marine infantry and helicopters at Chu Lai participated in [[Operation Double Eagle]]<ref name=Shulimson66/>{{rp|19\u201336}} On 27 February while several Battalions were absent on Operation Double Eagle the Vietcong attacked a 1/4 Marines outpost killing 5 Marines.<ref name=Shulimson66/>{{rp|36}}\n\nFrom 4\u20137 March the Chu Lai-based Marines and ARVN 2nd Division launched [[Operation Utah]] resulting in 98 Marines, 30 ARVN and almost 600 [[People's Army of Vietnam]] (PAVN) soldiers killed and 5 captured.<ref name=Shulimson66/>{{rp|109\u2013119}} From 20\u201327 March the 3/7 Marines and ARVN [[Republic of Vietnam Airborne Division|5th Airborne Battalion]] launched [[Operation Texas (1966)|Operation Texas]] resulting in 99 Marines and 283 PAVN/Vietcong killed.<ref name=Shulimson66/>{{rp|120\u20136}} On 28 March the 1/7 Marines launched [[Operation Indiana]] to assist the 3rd Battalion, 5th ARVN Regiment resulting in 11 Marines and 169 Vietcong killed.<ref name=Shulimson66/>{{rp|127\u20138}}\n\nOn 28 March 4 Marines moved their headquarters from Chu Lai to [[Phu Bai Combat Base]]<ref name=Shulimson66/>{{rp|69}} The 3/12 Marines also moved to Phu Bai in March and artillery support was taken over by the 11th Marines.<ref name=Shulimson66/>{{rp|277}}\n\nOn 29 March the [[1st Marine Division]] established its headquarters at Chu Lai. The 1st Division commander MGEN Lewis Fields created the Chu Lai Defense Command tasked with protecting the air base and the K\u1ef3 H\u00e0 Peninsula.<ref name=Shulimson66/>{{rp|128\u20139}}\n\nAlso in March the Force Logistics Support Unit became Force Logistics Support Group Bravo and [[Naval Mobile Construction Battalion 4]] began building permanent facilities at K\u1ef3 H\u00e0.<ref name=Shulimson66/>{{rp|288\u20139}}\n\nIn mid-April the [[2nd Battalion, 5th Marines]] replaced the 2/4 Marines which moved north to Danang. On 22 May [[1st Battalion, 5th Marines]] replaced the 3/1 Marines which also moved to Danang. On 27 May the [[5th Marine Regiment]] moved its headquarters to Chu Lai. By 1 June Marine Division had over 17,000 men in the expanded 340 square mile tactical area of operations around Chu Lai.<ref name=Shulimson66/>{{rp|130\u20131}}\n\nFrom 17\u201322 June 1 Marine Division launched [[Operation Kansas]] in the [[Que Son Valley]] resulting in 9 Marines and 85 PAVN killed.<ref name=Shulimson66/>{{rp|131\u20136}} From 6\u201314 July the Marines [[1st Reconnaissance Battalion]] launched [[Operation Washington]] in the [[Do Xa]] region west of Chu Lai, resulting in 15 Vietcong killed and 8 captured.<ref name=Shulimson66/>{{rp|212\u20133}} From 6\u201322 August the Marines and ARVN launched [[Operation Colorado|Operation Colorado/Lien Ket 52]] to engage the PAVN [[2nd Division (Vietnam)|2nd Division]] in the Que Son Valley.<ref name=Shulimson66/>{{rp|214\u201320}}\n\nOn 18 August the [[Republic of Korea]] [[2nd Marine Division (South Korea)|2nd Marine Brigade]] was deployed to Chu Lai and assigned an area of operations southeast of Chu lai, including the [[Batangan Peninsula]].<ref name=Shulimson66/>{{rp|223}}\n\nOn 10 October 1 Marine Division headquarters was moved from Chu Lai to Danang, replacing the 3rd Marine Division rear headquarters which moved from Danang to [[\u0110\u00f4ng H\u00e0 Combat Base|\u0110\u00f4ng H\u00e0]].<ref name=Shulimson66/>{{rp|223}}\n\nIn October [[94th Field Artillery Regiment|Battery A, 2nd Battalion, 18th Artillery]] was deployed to Chu Lai to support the Marine artillery. On 30 November the [[1st Field Artillery Group]] was deployed to Chu Lai to assume control of all artillery from the 11th Marines which had moved north to Danang.<ref name=Shulimson66/>{{rp|279\u201380}}\n\nUnits attached to MAG-36 at K\u1ef3 H\u00e0 during this period included:\n*[[VMM-165|HMM-165]] (from September)\n*[[VMM-261|HMM-261]] (until April)\n*[[VMM-262|HMM-262]] (from December)\n*[[HMH-361|HMM-361]] (June, August)\n*HMM-362 (April\u2013August)\n*HMM-363 (until July)\n*HMM-364 (until March, July\u2013October)\n*[[Marine Aviation Logistics Squadron 16|H&MS-16]] sub-unit one (January 1966)\n*VMO-6<ref name=Popasmoke/>\n\n===1967===\nFrom 21 April to 16 May the Marines launched [[Operation Union]] near the Que Son Valley resulting in 110 Marines and 865 PAVN/Vietcong killed.<ref name=Telfer>{{cite book|last=Telfer|first=Gary|title=U.S. Marines in Vietnam: Fighting the North Vietnamese 1967|publisher=History and Museums Division, Headquarters, U.S. Marine Corps|year=1984|isbn=978-1494285449}}{{PD-notice}}</ref>{{rp|63-8}}\n\nIn early April [[Military Assistance Command, Vietnam]] (MACV) gave instructions to commence the [[Task Force Oregon]] plan, which involved the movement of an Army task force to [[\u0110\u1ee9c Ph\u1ed5 Base Camp|\u0110\u1ee9c Ph\u1ed5]] and Chu Lai area to allow the 1st Marine Division to move north to Danang to support the 3rd Marine Division in northern I Corps.<ref name=Telfer/>{{rp|78}}<ref name=Stanton>{{cite book|last=Stanton|first=Shelby|title=Vietnam Order of Battle|publisher=Stackpole Books|year=2003|isbn=9780811700719|page=85}}</ref> Task Force Oregon comprised:\n*[[25th Infantry Division (United States)|3rd Brigade, 25th Infantry Division]]\n*[[101st Airborne Division|1st Brigade, 101st Airborne Division]]\n*[[196th Infantry Brigade (United States)|196th Light Infantry Brigade]]\n*[[11th Armored Cavalry Regiment|2nd Squadron, 11th Armored Cavalry]] (May\u2013August 1967)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|131}}\n\nOn 9 April the 196th Light Infantry Brigade arrived at Chu Lai, the Task Force headquarters was activated on 12 April, by 17 April the 196th had commenced [[Operation Lawrence]] west of the air base and by 26 April the Task Force had assumed control of the Chu Lai tactical area of operations.<ref name=Telfer/>{{rp|79}}\n\nFrom August\u2013September Task Force Oregon launched [[Operation Benton]] to the west of Chu Lai, resulting in 397 PAVN killed.<ref name=Telfer/>{{rp|119}}\n\nIn September 1967 the [[23rd Infantry Division (United States)|23rd Americal Division]] was reestablished from elements of Task Force Oregon with its headquarters at Chu Lai and would remain here until November 1971,<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|79}} its subordinate units based at Chu Lai were:\n*[[1st Cavalry Regiment (United States)|1st Squadron, 1st Cavalry]] (September 1967 \u2013 November 1968, November 1969 \u2013 August 1970, November 1970 \u2013 April 1971)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|124}}\n*[[11th Infantry Brigade (United States)|11th Infantry Brigade]]<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|85}}\n*196th Light Infantry Brigade (June\u2013October 1967, July 1968 \u2013 March 1971)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|88}}\n*[[198th Infantry Brigade (United States)|198th Infantry Brigade]] (December 1967 \u2013 November 1971)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|88}}\n*[[16th Field Artillery Regiment|3rd Battalion, 16th Artillery]] (June 1967 \u2013 October 1971)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|100}}\n*[[18th Field Artillery Regiment|3rd Battalion, 18th Artillery]] (April 1967 \u2013 October 1971)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|101}}\n*[[55th Air Defense Artillery Regiment|Battery G, 55th Artillery]] (February 1968 \u2013 July 1971)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|105}}\n*[[56th Air Defense Artillery Regiment|6th Battalion, 56th Artillery]] (1968 \u2013 June 1969)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|105}}\n*[[82nd Field Artillery Regiment|1st Battalion, 82nd Artillery]] (July 1968 \u2013 November 1971)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|107}}\n*[[82nd Field Artillery Regiment|3rd Battalion, 82nd Artillery]] (February 1969)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|107}}\n*[[16th Combat Aviation Brigade (United States)|16th Aviation Group]] (March 1969 \u2013 November 1971)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|110}} including:\n**[[14th Aviation Battalion]] (April 1967 \u2013 October 1971)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|114}}\n**[[123rd Aviation Battalion]] (December 1967 \u2013 November 1971)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|115}}\n**[[21st Aviation Company]] (June 1967 \u2013 November 1971)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|121}}\n**[[71st Aviation Company]] (September 1967 \u2013 October 1971)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|121}}\n*[[28th Engineer Battalion]] (December 1967 \u2013 November 1971)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|171}}\n*[[509th Signal Battalion]] (1967\u201368)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|185}}\n*[[523rd Signal Battalion]] (January 1968 \u2013 November 1971)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|185}}\n*[[74th Medical Battalion]] (October 1967 \u2013 November 1969)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|213}}\n*[[27th Surgical Hospital]] (March 1968 \u2013 June 1971)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|215}}\n*[[91st Evacuation Hospital]] (July 1969 \u2013 November 1971)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|216}}\n\nUnits attached to MAG-36 at K\u1ef3 H\u00e0 during this period included:\n*HMM-165 (until November)\n*[[HMM-263]] (from July\u2013November)\n*HMM-262 (until March)\n*HMM-362 (until June)\n*HMM-363 (January)\n*VMO-6 (until September)<ref name=Popasmoke/>\n\nIn October MAG-36 began to relocate from K\u1ef3 H\u00e0 to Phu Bai and by the end of the month most units had completed the move.<ref name=Telfer/>{{rp|211}}\n\nThe [[3rd Brigade Combat Team, 1st Cavalry Division|3rd Brigade, 1st Cavalry Division]] was based at Chu Lai from October 1967 \u2013 January 1968, constituent units included:\n*[[7th Cavalry Regiment|1st Battalion, 7th Cavalry]] (January 1968)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|127}}\n*[[7th Cavalry Regiment|2nd Battalion, 7th Cavalry]]<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|127}}\n*[[12th Cavalry Regiment|2nd Battalion, 12th Cavalry]] (October 1967 \u2013 January 1968)<ref name=Stanton/>{{rp|132}}\n\nIn late 1967 Force Logistics Group Bravo moved from Chu Lai to \u0110\u00f4ng H\u00e0, leaving only a reinforced supply company to handle logistics for the remaining Marines at Chu Lai.<ref name=Telfer/>{{rp|229}}\n\nIn 1967 a Naval Support Activity base was established at Chu Lai to provide logistics support for allied operations in southern I Corps.<ref name=Telfer/>{{rp|232}}\n\n===1968\u201371===\nOn 31 January 1968 as part of the [[Tet Offensive]] Vietcong rockets hit the FLSG Bravo ammunition dump destroying over 600 tons of bombs and bulk explosives.<ref name=Shulimson>{{cite book|last=Shulimson|first=Jack|title=U.S. Marines in Vietnam: 1968 The Defining Year|publisher=History and Museums Division, Headquarters, U.S. Marine Corps|year=1997|isbn= 0-16-049125-8}}{{PD-notice}}</ref>{{rp|583}}\n\nIn September 1968 the 2nd Light Anti-Aircraft Missile Battalion returned to the U.S.<ref name=Shulimson/>{{rp|414}}\n\nOn 27 November 1971 the 23rd Infantry Division turned over the base to the ARVN.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vietnam.ttu.edu/reports/images.php?img=/images/1683/168300010817.pdf|title=Headquarters MACV Command History 1971 Volume II|publisher=Headquarters United States Military Assistance Command, Vietnam|date=1971|accessdate=9 April 2020|page=J-37}}{{PD-notice}}</ref>\n\n==Current use==\nSatellite imagery shows that he base has been turned over to housing and farmland, while the port facilities remain in use.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Marine Corps}}\n\n[[Category:Military installations of the United States Marine Corps in South Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Installations of the United States Army in South Vietnam]]\n[[Category:Installations of the Army of the Republic of Vietnam]]\n", "name_user": "Mztourist", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e1967", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chu_Lai_Base_Area"}
